{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506374"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:42:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:42:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2532"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2532"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.46,0.06,0.2,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2532"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101537"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2532"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2532"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83976"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1331"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2425"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2426"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2457"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13090"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15613"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17334"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34553"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42518"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43178"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101537"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-year history of exertional chest pain that has remained unchanged in quality and intensity. He experiences chest discomfort every two weeks when playing golf, particularly when climbing a hill, and the pain resolves within seven minutes of rest. He has never experienced this pain at rest. He has a history of asthma, hypertension, and a 20 pack-year smoking history. An angiogram performed last year showed a 70% stenosis in a small distal right coronary artery, managed medically. His current medications are atorvastatin, salbutamol as needed, and aspirin. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with pulse rate 72/min, blood pressure 110/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are unremarkable. Ambulatory blood pressure monitoring confirms an average of 110/80 mmHg.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Initiate metoprolol","Recommend glyceryl trinitrate use prior to exercise","Advise reduction in exercise intensity","Refer for revascularisation therapy","Initiate nicorandil"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecommend glyceryl trinitrate use prior to exercise or exertion\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial step. This person has stable, predictable angina triggered by exertion, with symptoms that are infrequent. Prophylactic use of glyceryl trinitrate before anticipated exertion can prevent angina symptoms and is a safe, effective strategy in this context. This approach avoids unnecessary escalation of therapy and minimises risk of adverse effects from additional medications, especially given his relatively low blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitiate metoprolol\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate due to the patient\u0027s history of asthma with reactive airway, as beta blockers can precipitate bronchospasm. Additionally, his blood pressure is already at the lower end of the target range, so further reduction could cause hypotension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdvise reduction in exercise intensity\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended, as regular physical activity is important for cardiovascular health. The patient should be encouraged to remain active, with advice to stop if angina symptoms occur, but not to reduce activity solely to avoid symptoms that are otherwise well-managed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefer for revascularisation therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated, as the patient has stable symptoms, no evidence of acute coronary syndrome, and his previous angiogram showed a lesion not suitable for intervention. Revascularisation is reserved for refractory symptoms or high-risk features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitiate nicorandil\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary at this stage. Nicorandil is considered when first-line therapies are inadequate or contraindicated. In this case, symptoms are infrequent, predictable, and controlled with glyceryl trinitrate, and further vasodilator therapy could increase the risk of hypotension given his blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOngoing support for smoking cessation and optimisation of cardiovascular risk factors should also be addressed in follow-up.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Prophylactic glyceryl trinitrate spray before exertion can prevent angina symptoms in people with stable, predictable angina.","Beta blockers are contraindicated in people with asthma due to risk of bronchospasm.","Further anti-anginal medications or revascularisation are not indicated if symptoms are infrequent, predictable, and well-controlled."],"references":["Parker JD, Parker JO. Nitrate therapy for stable angina pectoris. N Engl J Med 1998; 338:520. Available at: https://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJM199802193380807","Gibbons RJ, Abrams J, Chatterjee K, Daley J, Deedwania PC, Douglas JS, et al. ACC/AHA 2002 guideline update for the management of patients with chronic stable angina--summary article: a report of the American College of Cardiology/American Heart Association Task Force on practice guidelines (Committee on the Management of Patients With Chronic Stable Angina). J Am Coll Cardiol. 2003 Jan 1;41(1):159-68. Available at: www.acc.org/qualityandscience/clinical/statements.html","Wee Y, Burns K, Bett N. Medical management of chronic stable angina. Aust Prescr. 2015 Aug;38(4):131-6. doi: 10.18773/austprescr.2015.042. Epub 2015 Aug 3. PMID: 26648642; PMCID: PMC4653970. Available at: https://australianprescriber.tg.org.au/articles/medical-management-of-chronic-stable-angina.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83976"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2532"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83976"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-02T14:46:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T14:47:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2532"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101537"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.e